This x 1000 if possible, mostly if you also have someone who can show you the ropes. The basic laws governing where you can shoot are fairly straightforward if you look them up (simple version is look for fire service roads, get a mile or two down them, and make sure you don't see any signs stating otherwise. Easier in some states than others.) But it's very important that you have a berm behind your targets and you know what's behind the range. You need to know where your bullets are going to end up.

If you don't have a buddy to take you, I'd say go for an outdoor range. They're less likely to have rentals, but a lot less crowded and stressful, and generally have more options. If you're into shotguns at all, trap and Skeet shooting are surprisingly easy to pick up and fun as fuck. A lot of outdoor ranges have trap throwers, and clay pigeons are affordable. I'll warn you though: right now ammunition is extremely difficult to find, unless that's the thing you're waiting to blow over.
